> In my opinion, from `vim.fn.exepath('ngserver')` we already get the "Angular VS Code extension path", so we don't need to search all `$XDG_DATA_PATH/nvim`

VSCode extension can get away with it because it can refer to its own install path; nvim-lspconfig does not install any language server so it must make some assumptions about where to find the executable. If the AngularLS doesn't have a global shim (like if it is installed in Neovim's data folder via Masor or another manager), it won't be enough. But many LS configs assume there is some globally available executable or shim for the language server.

@justinmk What do you think? Maybe we can work as other configs and pass the responsability of providing a shim for the server to the user, so we can do away with the glob inside Neovim's data foler.
